metadata.name: coalescence #28
metadata.description:
coalescence is a real-time interactive particle system. Tens of thousands of agents of multiple distinct species interact, cooperate, and compete with one another. Each agent leaves a trail as it moves, and reacts to the trails left behind by other agents, creating complex emergent structures.

Click and drag to erase trails, forcing the agents to rebuild their patterns anew.

Press "s" to save a screenshot.

You can use the url parameter "resolution" to set a fixed simulation resolution, e.g. "?resolution=4096". This can be used to capture high-quality screenshots.

metadata.name: Geometric colorful shapes 3 #38
metadata.description:
This art tool uses an algorithmic approach that includes genetic and selection processes to generate unique and colorful abstract shapes. With the ability to adjust various parameters, each design is truly one-of-a-kind, and you can easily save and share your creations using our unique hash function. So go ahead, get creative, and let the program surprise you with its endless possibilities! Remember, the program is the only creator of these colorful shapes, thanks to its algorithmic approach, and if you like the result, you can support my previous projects.
The program has a default resolution of 1500x1500.

metadata.name: Mi  #23
metadata.description:
"Mi" for Mimicry
By imitating the colours and shapes of nature, the project seeks to create a digital version of reality that is both familiar and surreal. The resulting landscapes are at once recognizable and otherworldly, inviting viewers to explore the boundaries between the natural and the artificial.

"Mi" as a musical note
"Mi" synthesises a noise function to create dramatic landscapes, much like a musician who manipulates the frequencies of a musical composition.

"Mi" for Mile/Minute
Creating art is a journey that can take us down unexpected paths, and "Mi" embraces the idea of exploration and experimentation.

Tech Note
Please use the quality settings (press "Q") to generate a higher quality image. The project has been optimised for maximum performance, so it can be rendered on older machines. You can also adjust the resolution to your liking by pressing "R".

Press "S" to save the image.

The code has been tested on my old MacBook and various Windows machines. For best results, please use a modern Chromium-based browser, and ensure that your browser supports WebGL 2.


superbialux

metadata.name: Ordinary Places #3
metadata.description:
‚ÄúOrdinary Places‚Äù is a fully-coded meditation on the poetic beauty of everyday landscapes. 

The architectural characters in these landscapes include water towers (inspired by Bernd & Hilla Becher‚Äôs ‚ÄúWater Tower‚Äù photography series), gas stations (inspired by Ed Ruscha‚Äôs ‚Äú26 Gasoline Stations‚Äù photography book), and barns (inspired by childhood memories on my grandfather‚Äôs farm). 

Yet, while these scenes may seem ordinary upon first glance, something darker lurks beneath the surface. The hidden secrets of these Ordinary Places can only be revealed through the minting process. In this sense, the outputs are not merely a collection individual scenes, but instead, a coherent world animated by shared themes and narratives.     

Pressing the down arrow saves the coded output as a .png image.

metadata.name: Extrusion - v2 #128
metadata.description:
Dear collectors,
Extrusion was originally published as Project #14512 on June 9, 2022.
(https://www.fxhash.xyz/generative/14512)
Due to a technical issue, Project #14512 has been hidden from the site and is being replaced by this reissued version.

_______________________________

Extrusion is a work that brings the generation of particles that perform smooth sinusoidal movements according to the evolution of the animation frames. Each frame registers its position with a slight shading, and with continuous stacking we get the impression of depth that I like to call 'pseudo-3D'.
The perception of movement is something that I really enjoy watching and I hope it can have the same effect on collectors and enthusiasts of animated arts. Even so, for those who prefer static art, the work is finished after a frame count (which may vary depending on its hash) by adding a grain texture followed by a thin black beveled frame with white passe-partout for better highlighting. the post-animation result.

The palette sets were carefully chosen, totaling 19 palettes with 6 colors each, separated into themes of environment, mood, styles, materials and other elements. Of these seven are monochromatic sets with a small rarity of being obtained.

The shapes of the particles vary between 8 pointed stars (rare), circles and vertical or horizontal bars and their trail changes a lot according to the frame count and total number of objects in the scene. Sometimes they look like they are dancing while moving around creating pseudo-three-dimensional objects.

The screens can be obtained in three different aspect ratios: 1x1 (square, more common), and two wide options (16x9 landscape and 9x16 portrait, a little rarer).

As already said and I always say: carefully chosen palettes!

_______________________________
Variety of editions is guaranteed by several features:
* Black or white backgrounds (for better highlighting of particles);
* 19 color palettes with 6 colors each where the rarest is BW (<6%)
* 3 aspect ratios: 1x1 (50%), 9x16 (25%) and 16x9 (25%)
* Controlled variety of scale;
* Controlled variety of particle number;
* Animation time;
* Shape type: circles (60%), bars (30%) and stars (10%);
* Animation with coordinated movement (12%);
* Super rare inverted move (5%)

_______________________________
Interactive instructions:
* Press [I] to change the inverted mode, if you have it.

_______________________________
Saving your .png file:
* Press [S] to save your .png file in screen size;
* Press [0] to save your .png file in qHD resolution;
* Press [1] to save your .png file in FHD resolution;
* Press [2] to save your .png file in UHD (4K) resolution;
* Press [3] to save your .png file in FUHD (8K) resolution;
(for higher resolutions, please wait up for few seconds until complete render)


Made with p5.js
_______________________________

June 2022 -> Dec2022

metadata.name: 7.356 degrees #170
metadata.description:
Start with something simple. Take four identical equilateral triangles and join them to form a pyramid. This is your building block ‚Äì a regular tetrahedron, the simplest possible three-dimensional figure.

When you connect five such pyramids by attaching their faces, you will be left with a thin empty space between the first and last: a volumetric angle of 7.356 degrees. It‚Äôs too small to fit another piece and too big to be lost in numerical imprecision.

It is a surprising imperfection. You would expect a tetrahedron to behave similarly to its two-dimensional ancestor. When you arrange equilateral triangles, one next to the other like tiles, you can cover two-dimensional space without leaving an empty spot. You may go on forever, covering infinite planes and be sure that the six angles that meet at each point will add up to the perfect 360 degrees.

In three dimensions, it is not like this: you cannot use your building block to fully fill a void. It‚Äôs as if the mathematical rules ‚Äìthe ones we tend to idealise for elegance, harmony, and infallibility‚Äì broke when you raise complexity.

But mathematical beauty does not reside in perfection. It is through these exceptions that complexity emerges. So keep building, face by face, one block at a time, and embrace the surprising, chaotic aesthetics that appears. A different type of harmony ‚Äì not based on impeccable proportions, but on unpredictability.

---

The colours of the structures are inspired by 16 paintings of Polish artists from the 19th and 20th centuries.

metadata.name: Ersbla #915
metadata.description:
Ersbla is part of the fxhash live minting experience at Proof of People, London 2022. 

It is the third entry in a series of abstract generative experiments inspired by the graphic and textile work of Anni and Josef Albers. As a follow-up to the 'Sabler' and 'Lebras' collections, 'Ersbla' produces textile effects using a combination of thousands of tiny dots arranged on variable grids, resulting in a wide variety of unique Bauhaus-inspired compositions in a variety of palettes.

Press 'S' to save a high-resolution 2400 x 3396 px image in PNG format.

Depending on the density of your output, please allow up to a few seconds for your edition to generate.

metadata.name: Iteration is Usually Recursive (Pt. 1) #83
metadata.description:
This is the companion piece released with 'Iteration is Usually Recursive ‚Äî Introduction: Finding answers in pre-computational art', the first in a series of essays, some long, some short, on generative art, theory and the practitioners of the medium. 

This piece started a simple experimen recreating George Nees‚Äô Schotter (1968)‚Äî a classic piece of generative art history ‚Äî as vanilla js SVG graphics. From there, I specifically developed it with non-plotter printing in mind, and more specific still, Riso Printing (think a scanner with a digital screen-printer MacGyver‚Äôd on). The palettes are taken from hex-estimated Risograph colour gamuts, with three layers being multiplied together to replicate, to some degree, the blending of the semi-transparent Risographic inks. Within this study, there‚Äôs a few different things going on, the initial setup is rectangles which cascade down the canvas, inheriting more extreme rotation as they get closer to the bottom (a la Schotter). The second is a subdivision of the shapes with filled circled, outlined circles and squares ‚Äî since in this study the base shapes are rectangles and not squares, distribution of the ‚Äòdithering‚Äô can be larger than a single ‚Äòpixel‚Äô size ‚Äî when these multiple layers overlap, the shapes produce a halftone-moire effect, forms and structures appear from the noise as the underlying patterns intersect. 

tx: Who?, Cosimo, Liam Egan, Andreas Rau, Louis

Licensing: CC-BY-NC-ND
